2 mathematical modeling of control systems
2.1 introduction
in study control system the reader must be able to model dynamic system in mathematical term and analyze they dynamic characteristic .
a mathematical model of a dynamic system be define as a set of equation that represent the dynamics of the system accurately , or at least fairly well .
note that a mathematical model be not unique to a give system .
a system may be represent in many different way and , therefore , may have many mathematical model , depend on one ’s perspective .
the dynamics of many system , whether they be mechanical , electrical , thermal , economic , biological , and so on , may be describe in term of differential equation .
such differential equation may be obtain by use physical law govern a particular system -- for example , newton ’s law for mechanical system and kirchhoff ’s law for electrical system .
we must always keep in mind that derive reasonable mathematical model be the most important part of the entire analysis of control system .
throughout this book we assume that the principle of causality apply to the system consider .
this mean that the current output of the system ( the output at time t = 0 ) depend on the past input ( the input for t ' 0 ) but do not depend on the future input ( the input for t ' 0 ) .
mathematical model .
mathematical model may assume many different form .
depend on the particular system and the particular circumstance , one mathematical model may be better suit than other model .
for example , in optimal control problem , it be advantageous to use state-space representation .
on the other hand , for the transient-response or frequency-response analysis of single-input , single-output , linear , time-invariant system , the transfer-function representation may be more convenient than any other .
once a mathematical model of a system be obtain , various analytical and computer tool can be use for analysis and synthesis purpose .
simplicity versus accuracy .
in obtain a mathematical model , we must make a compromise between the simplicity of the model and the accuracy of the result of the analysis .
in derive a reasonably simplify mathematical model , we frequently find it necessary to ignore certain inherent physical property of the system .
in particular , if a linear lumped-parameter mathematical model ( that be , one employ ordinary differential equation ) be desire , it be always necessary to ignore certain nonlinearity and distribute parameter that may be present in the physical system .
if the effect that these ignore property have on the response be small , good agreement will be obtain between the result of the analysis of a mathematical model and the result of the experimental study of the physical system .
in general , in solve a new problem , it be desirable to build a simplify model so that we can get a general feeling for the solution .
a more complete mathematical model may then be build and use for a more accurate analysis .
we must be well aware that a linear lumped-parameter model , which may be valid in low-frequency operation , may not be valid at sufficiently high frequency , since the neglect property of distribute parameter may become a important factor in the dynamic behavior of the system .
for example , the mass of a spring may be neglect in low-frequency operation , but it become a important property of the system at high frequency .
( for the case where a mathematical model involve considerable error , robust control theory may be apply .
robust control theory be present in chapter 10 . )
